<DOC><DOCNO> AP881212-0128 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1707EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Botswana-Raid     12-12 0244</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Botswana-Raid,0250</SECOND><HEAD>Two Killed in Raid on Village Near South African Border</HEAD><DATELINE>GABORONE, Botswana (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Armed men raided a village nearBotswana's border with South Africa on Monday, killing two peopleand burning several huts, a news agency reported.   Police told the Botswana Press Association they suspected``elements of the South African Defense Force'' were involved in theattack on Ditlharapeng village on the Molopo River, which marks theborder between Botswana and South Africa.   In South Africa, a military spokesman denied the allegation.   Botswana police said an ``incendiary device'' was used in theattack, adding that footprints of the attackers were traced back tothe river.   The raid came four days after two white South Africans capturedin an aborted raid in Botswana were sentenced to 10 years in prisonand eight lashes with a cane. Johannes Basson, 25, and TheodoreHermansen, 30, were apprehended following a June 20 clash in whichthree unarmed Botswana police officers were injured.   South Africa has staged periodic raids into neighboring countriesin recent years in search of members of the African NationalCongress, the main guerrilla group fighting the South Africangovernment. More than a dozen alleged South African agents have beencharged in Botswana and Zimbabwe this year for security-relatedoffenses.   Botswana says it is sympathetic to the aims of the guerrillagroup, but that it does not want its territory to be used as alauching site for raids into South Africa.</TEXT></DOC>